# Terminology & Cross-Reference Consistency

Use when editing **multiple lessons**, doing a **consistency pass**, or when concepts span modules (transport → routing → BGP → SDN).

## Layer stack (Lessons 1–2)

Always top-to-bottom when listing:

**Application → Transport → Network → Data Link → Physical**

Data unit names: **Message → Segment → Datagram → Frame → Bits**

Devices: **Hub** (bits) → **Switch/bridge** (MAC) → **Router** (IP)

## Routing scope (Lessons 3–4)

| Term | Meaning | Protocol examples |
|------|---------|-------------------|
| **Intradomain / IGP** | Within one AS | OSPF, RIP |
| **Interdomain** | Between ASes | BGP |
| **AS** (Autonomous System) | One org, one routing policy | — |
| **Forwarding** | Data plane, per-packet | lookup FIB |
| **Routing** | Control plane, builds tables | link-state, distance-vector |

Cross-link: Lesson 3 full guide ↔ `lesson-04/interdomain-routing.md` at the handoff point.

## Transport (Lesson 2)

- **Multiplexing/demultiplexing** — UDP 2-tuple, TCP 4-tuple
- **Reliability** — ARQ variants (Stop-and-Wait, Go-Back-N, Selective Repeat)
- **Flow control** vs **congestion control** — never conflate
- **AIMD**, **slow start**, **fast retransmit** — TCP-specific; cite when discussing fairness

## BGP & business (Lesson 4)

- **Peering** vs **transit** — different economic relationships
- **LocalPref**, **AS-PATH**, **MED** — attribute names as course defines them
- **Hot potato** vs **cold potato** routing
- **IXP**, **route server** — interconnection vocabulary

## Design principles (Lesson 1, referenced everywhere)

- **End-to-end principle** — smart edges, dumb core
- **Hourglass / ossification** — IP/TCP/UDP waist
- **EvoArch** — evolutionary architecture, not "Evolution Architecture"

## Cross-reference format

```markdown
See [Lesson 4](lesson-04/interdomain-routing.md) for BGP.
For plain-language version, see the [Plain-language guide](lesson-04-plain-language.md).
```

Use relative paths from `docs/`. When updating a term in one lesson, grep `docs/` for the old phrasing.

## Common inconsistencies to fix

| Wrong | Right |
|-------|-------|
| "inter-domain" / "intra-domain" (hyphenated) | intradomain / interdomain (match existing docs) |
| "packet" at every layer | segment, datagram, frame when layer matters |
| "OSI model has 5 layers" | OSI has **7**; Internet model has **5** |
| NAT as E2E-friendly | NAT **violates** end-to-end |
| Wi-Fi error correction as E2E violation | Link-layer checking is **not** a violation (noisy medium) |

## grep before bulk edits

```bash
rg "inter-domain|intra-domain" docs/
rg "end.to.end|E2E" docs/
```

Align with the majority usage in the most recently edited lesson file for that module.
